<subsection xml:id="subsec-area-of-segments" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
    <title>Area of Segments</title>
    <objectives component="outcomes">
        <introduction xml:id="auto_d51wi006">
            <p xml:id="auto_xlun8ocx">
            <dl>
                <li xml:id="auto_eqiibfpt">
                    <title>Strand</title>
                    <p xml:id="auto_3l6kjzoj">
                        2.0 Measurements and Geometry
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li xml:id="auto_t70tju3g">
                    <title>Sub-Strand</title>
                    <p xml:id="auto_bz9y0cne">
                        2.6 Area of a Part of a Circle
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li xml:id="auto_ucklze15">
                    <title>Specific Learning Outcomes</title>
                    <p xml:id="auto_fj384j6v">
                        Work out the area of a segment of a circle in real-life situations
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li xml:id="auto_7zdudkzx" component="lesson-plan">
                    <title>Grade Level</title>
                    <p xml:id="auto_ffqbz2fv">
                        10
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li xml:id="auto_z0x0mnca" component="lesson-plan">
                    <title>Estimated Duration</title>
                    <p xml:id="auto_6kdcrvgg">
                        40 minutes
                    </p>
                </li>
            </dl>
            </p>
            <p xml:id="auto_nwitzy3i" component="lesson-plan">
                <p xml:id="auto_42di93tw"> Upon completion of this lesson, learners will be able to:
                <ol>
                    <li xml:id="auto_ahte6noq">
                        <p xml:id="auto_bi8rwzvt">
                            <alert>Know (Conceptual Understanding):</alert> Define what a segment is and understand the relationship between a sector and a triangle within a segment.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li xml:id="auto_ajx8ey85">
                        <p xml:id="auto_lk2wlypi">
                            <alert>Do (Procedural Skill):</alert> Calculate the area of a segment using <m>\text{Area of segment} = \text{Area of sector} - \text{Area of triangle}</m>.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li xml:id="auto_yyjvcj48">
                        <p xml:id="auto_xy88zcnf">
                            <alert>Apply (Application/Problem-Solving):</alert> Solve real-life problems involving areas of segments, such as cake slices, mudguards and park designs.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                </ol>
                </p>
            </p>
        </introduction>
    </objectives>
        <axiom component="resources">
        <!-- Link to blurb -->
        <xi:include href="../../resources-blurb-lesson.ptx" />

        <sbsgroup widths="45% 45%" margins="2% 2%">
            <sidebyside>
                <p xml:id="auto_h3akb65p">
                    <dataurl source="lesson_plans/measurements-and-geometry/area-of-a-part-of-a-circle/area-of-segments.pdf"> Lesson Plan </dataurl>
                </p>
                <p xml:id="auto_l50nhaj9">
                    <dataurl source="lesson_plans/measurements-and-geometry/area-of-a-part-of-a-circle/step-by-step-guide_area-of-segments.pdf"> Step-by-Step Guide </dataurl>
                </p>
            </sidebyside>
        </sbsgroup>
    </axiom>
    <xi:include href="../../resources-materials.ptx" />

    <axiom component="lesson-plan">
        <title>Phase 1: Problem-Solving and Discovery</title>
        <p xml:id="auto_sd8fsahn">
            <alert>Expected Time:</alert> 15 minutes
        </p>
        <p xml:id="auto_g3ib284s">
            <alert>Grouping:</alert> Work in groups
        </p>
        <p xml:id="auto_a8qgaler">
            <alert>Teacher Questions During Discovery:</alert>
        </p>
        <p xml:id="auto_unlsi71d">
            <ul>
                <li xml:id="auto_jwj8ejti">
                    <p xml:id="auto_hqwlyomr"><q>What is a segment?</q></p>
                </li>
                <li xml:id="auto_camc2max">
                    <p xml:id="auto_596vzi9d"><q>How is a segment different from a sector?</q></p>
                </li>
                <li xml:id="auto_r6q5m7cj">
                    <p xml:id="auto_rjaoxooh"><q>What shapes do you see inside the segment?</q></p>
                </li>
                <li xml:id="auto_f3qwn0yf">
                    <p xml:id="auto_6knx9k41"><q>How did you calculate the area of the segment?</q></p>
                </li>
            </ul>
        </p>
        <p xml:id="auto_1i6d0pa9">
            <alert>Teacher Role:</alert> Circulate among groups, ensuring learners understand how to draw chords and measure angles accurately. For struggling groups, prompt: <q>Let us find the area of the sector first. Then find the area of the triangle. What do we do next?</q> For early finishers: <q>Can you write a general formula for finding the area of any segment?</q> Identify 2–3 groups with clear findings to share with the class.
        </p>
        <p xml:id="auto_gnkhrlsy">
            <alert>Expected Responses:</alert> The area of a segment equals the area of the sector minus the area of the triangle.
        </p>
    </axiom>


    
    <activity xml:id="auto_4y511x5c">
        <p xml:id="auto_qukpaxt8">
            <m>\textbf{Work in groups}</m>
        </p>
        <p xml:id="auto_iqsukdch">
            <term>What you require;</term> 
        </p>
        <p xml:id="auto_5t8odr4s">
            <ul xml:id="auto_9qncgj50">
                <li xml:id="auto_sply8hjw">
                    <p xml:id="auto_frrgc2bb">
                        A compass,
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li xml:id="auto_umb8f72n">
                    <p xml:id="auto_twkucj2a">
                        A ruler,
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li xml:id="auto_27yfoo4f">
                    <p xml:id="auto_yiy9czon">
                        A protractor,
                    </p>
                </li>
                
                <li xml:id="auto_e41n449p">
                    <p xml:id="auto_fo13cjkc">
                        A scientific calculator,
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li xml:id="auto_ritankly">
                    <p xml:id="auto_93pw1uw5">
                        A worksheet with given radii and angles
                    </p>
                </li>
            </ul>
        </p>
        <p xml:id="auto_uz2fobyq">
            <ol xml:id="auto_8eeo8oc3">
                <li xml:id="auto_b9go0w0o">
                    <p xml:id="auto_jsnwknjk">
                         Use a compass to draw a circle of radius <m>r</m>.
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li xml:id="auto_rd1huuyf">
                    <p xml:id="auto_ljzdmtvd">
                        Draw a chord across the circle using a ruler.
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li xml:id="auto_w84ikwj8">
                    <p xml:id="auto_qhpj0cwu">
                        Use a protractor to measure the angle subtended at the center by the chord.
                    </p>
                    <p xml:id="auto_it1a6zhi">
                        Shade the segment formed
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li xml:id="auto_dewa41pl">
                    <p xml:id="auto_c4mxn6o4">
                        Find the area of the segment part and record your results.
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li xml:id="auto_g2v3u55z">
                    <p xml:id="auto_pmeydzwa">
                        Perform the same process for different chords and angles eg <m>70^\circ, \,90^\circ,\,120^\circ,\,150^\circ...</m>
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li xml:id="auto_ctwuy7re">
                    <p xml:id="auto_96l35vh2">
                        Discuss your work with other learners in your class.
                    </p>
                </li>
            </ol>
        </p>
    </activity>

    <axiom component="lesson-plan">
        <title>Phase 2: Structured Instruction</title>
        <p xml:id="auto_a01p1lzb">
            <alert>Expected Time:</alert> 10 minutes
        </p>
        <p xml:id="auto_64sdvr2z">
            <alert>Scaffolding Strategies to Address Misconceptions:</alert>
        </p>
        <p xml:id="auto_067hajb8">
            <ul>
                <li xml:id="auto_ndnkdrfe">
                    <p xml:id="auto_ffuyb0kw"><alert>Misconception:</alert> <q>A segment is the same as a sector.</q> <alert>Clarification:</alert> A segment is bounded by a chord and an arc, while a sector is bounded by two radii and an arc.</p>
                </li>
                <li xml:id="auto_v7gi78x4">
                    <p xml:id="auto_xtbzbkf4"><alert>Misconception:</alert> <q>I add the area of the sector and the triangle.</q> <alert>Clarification:</alert> You subtract the area of the triangle from the area of the sector.</p>
                </li>
                <li xml:id="auto_xrrbdzrd">
                    <p xml:id="auto_h61dhga6"><alert>Misconception:</alert> <q>I can use any triangle formula.</q> <alert>Clarification:</alert> Use <m>A = \frac{1}{2}ab\sin\theta</m> because you know the two sides (radii) and the included angle.</p>
                </li>
                <li xml:id="auto_tmudcc96">
                    <p xml:id="auto_jr56ew2i"><alert>Misconception:</alert> <q>The angle in the triangle formula is different from the sector angle.</q> <alert>Clarification:</alert> It is the same angle subtended at the centre.</p>
                </li>
            </ul>
        </p>
    </axiom>

    <p xml:id="auto_xyagzjvv">
        <m>\textbf{Key Takeaway}</m>
    </p>

    <p xml:id="auto_ipgxjwa2">
        A <m>\textbf{segment} </m> is the region of a circle bounded by a chord and an arc as shown in the figure below.
    </p>
    <image width="50%">
    <latex-image label="Segment1">
        \begin{tikzpicture}
            % Draw the circle
            \draw[thick] (0,0) circle (3);
            
            % Define points for the chord
            \coordinate (A) at (3,0);
            \coordinate (B) at (-1.5,2.598);
            \coordinate (O) at (0,0);
            
            % Draw the chord
            \draw[thick] (A) -- (B);
            
            % Draw the radii
            \draw[thick] (O) -- (A);
            \draw[thick] (O) -- (B);
            
            % Shade the segment (Use a darker blue)
            \fill[blue!60, opacity=0.7] (A) arc[start angle=0, end angle=120, radius=3cm] -- (B) -- cycle;
            
            % Draw the arc (on top for visibility)
            \draw[thick] (A) arc[start angle=0, end angle=120, radius=3cm];
            
            % Label the points
            \node[right] at (3,0) {A};
            \node[above] at (B) {B};
            \node[below] at (O) {O};
            
            % Mark the angle
            \draw[thick] (0.8,0) arc[start angle=0, end angle=120, radius=0.8cm];
            \node at (0.7,0.6) {\(\theta\)};
            
            \draw [very thick,-&gt;](1,2.8)--(2,3) ;
            \draw [very thick,-&gt;](1,1.15)--(3.5,1);
            
            
            \node [right] at (2,3){\textbf{Arc}};
            \node [right] at (3.5,1){\textbf{Chord}};
            \node [below] at (1.5,0){$r=q$};
        \end{tikzpicture}
    </latex-image>
        
        
    </image>
    <p xml:id="auto_4q6m19gg">
        The shaded region is a segment of the circle with centre <m>O</m> and the radius <m>q</m>
    </p>
    <p xml:id="auto_l6untf5n">
        <m>\textbf{Area of a segment of a circle.}</m>
    </p>
    <p xml:id="auto_o772lg7b">
        The area of a segment is given by;
    </p>
    <p xml:id="auto_dnm05m86">
        <m> \text{Area of a segment}=\text{Area of sector}-\text{Area of  triangle}</m>
    </p>

    <axiom component="lesson-plan">
        <title>Phase 3: Practice and Application</title>
        <p xml:id="auto_6g6e7thj">
            <alert>Expected Time:</alert> 10 minutes
        </p>
        <p xml:id="auto_uutyej4k">
            <alert>Objective:</alert> Learners apply the segment formula to solve varied problems. Emphasise the two-step process: find sector area, then subtract triangle area.
        </p>
        <p xml:id="auto_ridc233g">
            <alert>Teacher's Role:</alert> Work through the first example on the board step by step. Allow learners to attempt the second example in pairs. Circulate and provide support as needed.
        </p>
    </axiom>

    <example xml:id="auto_wln6g35q">
        <statement>
            <p xml:id="auto_cq39dfe8">
                A chord in a circle of radius <m>7\, cm</m> subtends an angle of <m> 75^\circ</m> at the center as shown below. Find the area of the segment.
            </p>
            <image width="50%">
            <latex-image label="Segment2">
                \begin{tikzpicture}
                    % Draw the circle
                    \draw[thick] (0,0) circle (3);
                    
                    % Define points for the chord
                    \coordinate (A) at (3,0);
                    \coordinate (B) at (0,3);
                    \coordinate (O) at (0,0);
                    
                    % Draw the chord
                    \draw[thick] (A) -- (B);
                    
                    % Draw the radii
                    \draw[thick] (O) -- (A);
                    \draw[thick] (O) -- (B);
                    
                    % Shade the segment (darker blue for visibility)
                    \fill[very thick,green!60, opacity=0.7] (A) arc[start angle=0, end angle=90, radius=3cm] -- (B) -- cycle;
                    
                    % Draw the arc
                    \draw[thick] (A) arc[start angle=0, end angle=90, radius=3cm];
                    
                
                    
                    % Mark the angle
                    \draw[very thick] (0.7,0) arc[start angle=0, end angle=90, radius=0.7cm];
                    \node [right]at (0.7,0.5) {\(75^\circ\)};
                    \node[left] at (0,1.5){\textbf{7 cm}};
                \end{tikzpicture}
            </latex-image>
            
                
            </image>
        </statement>
        <solution>
            <p xml:id="auto_znkj3qxb">
                To find the area of the segment, you the area of the triangle and subtract from the area of the sector.
            </p>
            <p xml:id="auto_7upf8u8x">
                <m>\textbf{Area of sector }</m>
            </p>
            <p xml:id="auto_jkjd1n2x">
                <m>A= \frac{\theta}{ 360} \times \pi r^2</m>
            </p>
            <p xml:id="auto_5f8gw0vq">
                <md>
                    <mrow> A=\amp \frac{75^\circ}{ 360} \times \frac{22}{7} \times  7^2 </mrow>
                    <mrow> =\amp \frac{5}{24} \times \frac{22}{7} \times 49</mrow>
                    <mrow> =\amp \frac{385}{12} </mrow>
                    <mrow> =\amp 32.0833 \,cm^2 </mrow>
                    

                
                </md>
            </p>
            <p xml:id="auto_m1m3as40">
                <m>\textbf{Area of a triangle }</m>
            </p>
            <p xml:id="auto_61o3x967">
                <m>A= \frac{1}{2} ab sin \,\theta</m>
            </p>
            <p xml:id="auto_hkkry3vb">
                Where <m>a=7\,cm \,\text{and} \,b= 7 \,cm</m>
            </p>
            <p xml:id="auto_xdcm0mo4">
                <md>
                    <mrow> A=\amp  </mrow>
                    <mrow> =\amp \frac{1}{2} \times  7 \times 7\times \times  sin \,75^\circ</mrow>
                    <mrow> =\amp  \frac{1}{2} \times  49 \times  sin \,75^\circ</mrow>
                    <mrow> =\amp  23.6652 \,cm^2</mrow>
                    
                    

                
                </md>
            </p>
            <p xml:id="auto_aqjeraa5">
                Therefor,
            </p>
            <p xml:id="auto_25nywtia">
                <md>
                    <mrow>A= \amp 32.0833 \,cm^2- 23.6652 \,cm^2 </mrow>
                    <mrow>= \amp 8.4181\,cm^2</mrow>
                </md>
            </p>
        </solution>
    </example>
    <example xml:id="auto_xtcb957a">
        <statement>
            <p xml:id="auto_to3v8s1n">
                A chord XY of length <m>14 \,cm</m> is
                drawn in a circle with centre O and
                radius <m>8 cm</m>, as in the figure below
            </p>
            <image width="50%">
            <latex-image label="Segment3">
                \begin{tikzpicture}
                    % Draw the circle
                    \draw [very thick] (0,0) circle (6.4cm);
                    
                    % Define points
                    \coordinate (O) at (0,0);
                    \coordinate (X) at (-6,-2);
                    \coordinate (Y) at (6,-2);
                    \coordinate (N) at (0,-2);
                    \coordinate (P) at (0,-6.4);
                    
                    % Draw triangle
                    \draw [very thick] (O) -- (X) -- (Y) -- cycle;
                    \draw [thick] (O) -- (N);
                    \draw [thick] (N) -- (X);
                    \draw [thick] (N) -- (Y);

                    
                    
                
                    
                    % Right angle marker at N
                    \draw [very thick](N) ++(-0.3,0) -- ++(0,0.3) -- ++(0.3,0);
                    
                

                    % Shaded segment
                    % Draw labels
                    \node[above] at (O) {\textbf{O}};
                    \node[left] at (X) {\textbf{X}};
                    \node[right] at (Y) {\textbf{Y}};
                    \node[below] at (P) {\textbf{P}};
                    \node[below] at (N) {\textbf{N}};
                    
                    % Length labels
                    \node[left] at (-2,0) {\huge 8 cm};
                    \node[below] at (0,-2.3) {\huge 14 cm};

                \end{tikzpicture}
            </latex-image>
                
                
            </image>
            <p xml:id="auto_ze6niuvx">
                Calculate:
            </p>
            <p xml:id="auto_ieumjg5o">
                <ol xml:id="auto_g4ly6fts" marker="(a)">
                    <li xml:id="auto_mfca45km">
                        <p xml:id="auto_orrbpwf8">
                            the distance ON.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li xml:id="auto_fx9kagip">
                        <p xml:id="auto_cha81re8">
                            the area of the sector OXPY.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li xml:id="auto_ofh60v7t">
                        <p xml:id="auto_cnbgyspf">
                            the area of triangle OXY
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li xml:id="auto_b1qon853">
                        <p xml:id="auto_d459mmln">
                            the area of the minor segment.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li xml:id="auto_20bnrgew">
                        <p xml:id="auto_tof1vq87">
                            the area of the major segment.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                </ol>
            </p>
        </statement>
        <solution>
            <p xml:id="auto_rvdxi3e6">Given a circle with center <m>O</m>, radius 
            <m>8</m> cm, and a chord <m>XY</m> of length <m>14\,cm</m> , 
            we find the required values step by step.</p>
            <p xml:id="auto_4v3ekqk6">
                <ol xml:id="auto_bfzv6c4o" marker="(a)">
                    <li xml:id="auto_303fbfcv">
                        <p xml:id="auto_ct1d3uhi">Finding the Distance <m>\text{ON}</m></p>
                        <p xml:id="auto_87zfes4k">
                            Since ON is the perpendicular bisector of XY, 
                            we use the right triangle ONX where:
                        </p>
                        <p xml:id="auto_ghnmy79d">
                            <md>
                                <mrow> \text{OX}=\amp 8\,cm (\text{radius}) </mrow>
                                <mrow> \text{NX}=\amp \frac{\text{XY}}{2} </mrow>
                                <mrow>= \amp \frac{12}{2} </mrow>
                                <mrow>= \amp 7\,cm</mrow>
                            </md>
                        </p>
                        <p xml:id="auto_od725miu">
                            Using Pythagoras' Theorem in <m>\triangle</m> ONX:
                        </p>
                        <p xml:id="auto_wxfqq422">
                            <md>
                                <mrow>\text{ON}^2+ \text{NX}^2 =\amp \text{OX}^2</mrow>
                                <mrow> \text{ON}^2+ 7^2= \amp 8^2 </mrow>
                                <mrow> \text{ON}^2+ 49= \amp 64 </mrow>
                                <mrow> \text{ON}^2=\amp 64-49</mrow>
                                <mrow>\text{ON}^2= \amp 15 </mrow>
                                <mrow> \text{ON} =\amp \sqrt{15} </mrow>
                                <mrow> ​≈\amp  3.87 \,cm</mrow>
                            </md>
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li xml:id="auto_lsthyvt4">
                        <p xml:id="auto_hyvf3t31">
                            Finding the area of sector OXPY.
                        </p>
                        <p xml:id="auto_v4vcvl4i">
                            Finding the <m>\angle</m> XOY which is given by:
                        </p>
                        <p xml:id="auto_ffejjqbw">
                            <md>
                                <mrow> cos\,\theta= \amp  (\frac{\text{XN}}{\text{XO}} )</mrow>
                                <mrow> =\amp \frac{7}{8} </mrow>
                                <mrow> =\amp 0.875 </mrow>
                                <mrow> \theta=\amp cos^{-1}(0.875) </mrow>
                                <mrow> =\amp 28.9550^\circ </mrow>
                            </md>
                        </p>
                        <p xml:id="auto_h3izy4w3">therefor, <m>\angle \text{XOY}= 28.9550^\circ\times 2</m> </p>
                        <p xml:id="auto_y6l28ooa">
                            <me>=57.9100^\circ</me>
                        </p>
                        <p xml:id="auto_900oe31q">
                            The area of a sector is:
                        </p>
                        <p xml:id="auto_unc9ggf9">
                            <md>
                                <mrow> A=\amp  \frac{\theta}{360} \times \pi r^2</mrow>
                                <mrow> =\amp \frac{57.9100}{360} \times \pi 8^2 </mrow>
                                <mrow> =\amp  \frac{57.9100}{360} \times \frac{22}{7} \times 64</mrow>

                                <mrow> =\amp 32.3561 \,cm^2 </mrow>
                                
                            </md>
                        </p>
                        <p xml:id="auto_x2kpz71o">
                            Therefore, area of sector OXPY <m>=  32.3561 \,cm^2</m>
                        </p>

                    </li>
                    <li xml:id="auto_zpkpntgm">
                        <p xml:id="auto_18ocp76g">
                            Finding the area of triangle OXY
                        </p>
                        <p xml:id="auto_2gvpjy0q">
                            <md>
                                <mrow> \text{Area}= \amp \frac{1}{2} \times \text{base} \times \text{height} </mrow>
                                <mrow> =\amp  \frac{1}{2} \times 14 \times 3.87 \,cm </mrow>
                                <mrow>= \amp 7 \times 3.87 \,cm  </mrow>
                                <mrow> =\amp  27.09 \,cm^2</mrow>
                            </md>
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li xml:id="auto_gzbsoonb">
                        <p xml:id="auto_hzlvzk28">
                            Finding the area of the minor segment.
                        </p>
                        <p xml:id="auto_z55tl9y8">
                            <m>\text{Area of minor segment}=\text{Area of sector}- \text{Area of} \triangle \text{OXY}</m>
                        </p>
                        <p xml:id="auto_ss5wsxt4">
                            <md>
                                <mrow> \text{Area of minor segment}=\amp  </mrow>
                                <mrow> =\amp 32.3561 \,cm^2-27.09 \,cm^2 </mrow>
                                <mrow> =\amp 5.2661\,cm^2 </mrow>
                            </md>
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li xml:id="auto_bcpex99u">
                        <p xml:id="auto_4blsdexv">
                            Finding the area of the major segment
                        </p>
                        <p xml:id="auto_xob7sd40">
                            Area of major segment <m>=</m> Total circle area<m>-</m>Area of minor segment
                        </p>
                        <p xml:id="auto_irp1dw43">
                            Area of a circle.
                        </p>
                        <p xml:id="auto_56g9bq8l">
                            <md>
                                <mrow>A=  \amp \pi r^2 </mrow>
                                <mrow> =\amp \frac{22}{7} \times 8^2 </mrow>
                                <mrow> =\amp \frac{22}{7} \times 64 </mrow>
                                <mrow> =\amp 201.1429 \,cm^2 </mrow>
                                
                            </md>
                        </p>
                        <p xml:id="auto_y4rneqdi">
                            Therefore, Area of major segment is 
                        </p>
                        <p xml:id="auto_pkte08me">
                            <md>
                                <mrow>= \amp 201.1429 \,cm^2- 5.2661\,cm^2</mrow>
                                <mrow> =\amp 195.8768\,cm^2 </mrow>
                            </md>
                        </p>
                    </li>
                </ol>
            </p>
        </solution>

    </example>
 <axiom component="lesson-plan">
        <title>Phase 4: Assessment — Exit Ticket</title>
        <p xml:id="auto_r6eslumv">
            <alert>Expected Time:</alert> 5 minutes
        </p>
        <p xml:id="auto_kl2uro8n">
            <alert>Instructions:</alert> Learners complete the exercises individually. Collect responses as an exit ticket.
        </p>
        <p xml:id="auto_rhum6ocz">
            <alert>Answer Key (Teacher Reference):</alert>
        </p>
        <p xml:id="auto_m902rxdh">
            <ol marker="1.">
                <li xml:id="auto_1qpn1k7b">
                    <p xml:id="auto_8cygcsmi">
                        <m>r = 5\,cm</m> (by Pythagoras, <m>r^2 = 4^2 + 3^2</m>). Sector area <m>\approx 23.18\,cm^2</m>. Triangle area <m>= 12\,cm^2</m>. Segment <m>\approx 11.18\,cm^2</m>.
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li xml:id="auto_u58tg5gk">
                    <p xml:id="auto_t4eyr5xq">
                        Sector <m>= \frac{75}{360}\times\pi\times 15^2 \approx 147.32\,cm^2</m>. Triangle <m>= \frac{1}{2}(15)(15)\sin 75^\circ \approx 108.67\,cm^2</m>. Segment <m>\approx 38.65\,cm^2</m>.
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li xml:id="auto_iir50s7o">
                    <p xml:id="auto_oh1mmuof">
                        Sector <m>= \frac{60}{360}\times\pi\times 30^2 \approx 471.43\,cm^2</m>. Triangle <m>= \frac{1}{2}(30)(30)\sin 60^\circ \approx 389.71\,cm^2</m>. Segment <m>\approx 81.72\,cm^2</m>.
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li xml:id="auto_2g2jt7me">
                    <p xml:id="auto_il9o181f">
                        Sector <m>= \frac{120}{360}\times\pi\times 20^2 \approx 419.05\,m^2</m>. Triangle <m>= \frac{1}{2}(20)(20)\sin 120^\circ \approx 173.21\,m^2</m>. Segment <m>\approx 245.84\,m^2</m>.
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li xml:id="auto_3yzlyzn1">
                    <p xml:id="auto_q8fvtf0w">
                        Sector <m>= \frac{120}{360}\times\pi\times 13^2 \approx 177.05\,cm^2</m>. Triangle <m>= \frac{1}{2}(13)(13)\sin 120^\circ \approx 73.18\,cm^2</m>. Segment <m>\approx 103.87\,cm^2</m>.
                    </p>
                </li>
            </ol>
        </p>
    </axiom>

    <exercises>
        <exercise>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    In the figure below, ADC is a chord
                    of a circle with centre O passing
                    through A, B and C. BD is a
                    perpendicular bisector of AC. AD <m>=
                    4</m> cm and BD <m>= 2</m> cm. 
                </p>
                <image width="50%">
                <latex-image label="Segment4">
                    \begin{tikzpicture}[scale=1.2]
                        
                        % Coordinates
                        \coordinate (O) at (0,3);
                        \coordinate (A) at (-2,0);
                        \coordinate (C) at (2,0);
                        \coordinate (D) at (0,0);
                        \coordinate (B) at (0,-1);

                        % Lines
                        \draw [fill=white,very thick](O) -- (A) -- (C) -- cycle; % Triangle OAC
                        \draw (A) -- (C);
                        \draw [very thick](D) -- (B);

                        % Arc
                        \draw [very thick] (A) to[out=-60,in=-120] (C);

                        % Right angle mark
                        \draw (0,-0.2) -- (0.2,-0.2) -- (0.2,0);

                        % Labels
                        \node[above] at (O) {O};
                        \node[left] at (A) {A};
                        \node[right] at (C) {C};
                        \node[above] at (D) {D};
                        \node[below] at (B) {B};
                        \node[above right] at (-1,0) {4 cm};
                        \node[right] at (0,-0.5) {2 cm};
                    \end{tikzpicture}
                </latex-image>
                    
                </image>
                <p>
                    Calculate:
                </p>
                <p>
                    <ol marker= "(a)">
                        <li>
                            <p>
                                The radius OA.
                            </p>
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            <p>
                               The area of the sector OABC. 
                            </p>
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            <p>
                                The area of the segment ABCD.
                            </p>
                        </li>
                    </ol>
                </p>
            </statement>
            <answer>
                <p>
                    <ol marker= "(a)">
                        <li>
                            <p>
                               <m>4.47</m> cm
                            </p>
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            <p>
                                <m>18.52 \;\text{cm}^2</m>
                            </p>
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            <p>
                                <m>8.8 \;\text{cm}^2</m>
                            </p>
                        </li>
                    </ol>
                </p>
            </answer>
        </exercise>
        <exercise>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    A circular table has a radius of <m>15 \,cm</m>. A slice of cake is cut out, forming a <m>75^\circ </m> segment. 
                    Find the area of the cake slice not covered by the straight cut
                </p>
            </statement>
            <answer>
                <p>
                    <m>147.1 \;\text{cm}^2</m>
                </p>
            </answer>
        </exercise>
        <exercise>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    A wheel of a car has a radius of <m>30</m> cm. A mudguard covers a <m>60^\circ</m> segment of the wheel. 
                    Find the area of the covered segment.
                </p>
            </statement>
            <answer>
                <p>
                    <m>471.3 \;\text{cm}^2</m>
                </p>
            </answer>
        </exercise>
        <exercise>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    A circular park has a radius of <m>20</m> meters. A walking path cuts across the park, 
                    forming a chord that subtends an angle of <m>120^\circ</m> at the center as shown below.
                </p>
                <image width="50%">
                <latex-image label="Segment5">
                    \begin{tikzpicture}
                        % Draw the circle
                        \draw[very thick] (0,0) circle (3);
                        
                        % Define points for the chord
                        \coordinate (A) at (3,0);
                        \coordinate (B) at (-1.5,2.598);
                        \coordinate (O) at (0,0);
                        
                        % Draw the chord
                        \draw[thick] (A) -- (B);
                        
                        % Draw the radii
                        \draw[thick] (O) -- (A);
                        \draw[thick] (O) -- (B);
                        
                        % Shade the segment (darker for visibility)
                        \fill[cyan!60, opacity=0.7] (A) arc[start angle=0, end angle=120, radius=3cm] -- (B) -- cycle;
                        
                        % Draw the arc
                        \draw[thick] (A) arc[start angle=0, end angle=120, radius=3cm];
                        
                    
                        % Mark the angle
                        \draw[thick] (0.7,0) arc[start angle=0, end angle=120, radius=0.7cm];
                        \node [right]at (0.5,0.3) {\(120^\circ\)};
    
                    \end{tikzpicture}
                </latex-image>
                   
                </image>
                <p>
                    Determine the area of te segment formed? 
                </p>
            </statement>
            <answer>
                <p>
                    <m>245.5 \;\text{m}^2</m>
                </p>
            </answer>
        </exercise>
        <exercise>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    A chord XY subtends an angle of
                    <m>120^\circ</m> at the centre of a circle of
                    radius <m>13\, cm</m>. Calculate the area of
                    the minor segment.
                </p>
            </statement>
            <answer>
                <p>
                    <m>103.7 \;\text{cm}^2</m>
                </p>
            </answer>
        </exercise>
    </exercises>

    <axiom component="lesson-plan">
        <title>Differentiation</title>
        <p xml:id="auto_a8vruhh7">
            <alert>Struggling Learners:</alert>
        </p>
        <p xml:id="auto_iezspobo">
            <ul>
                <li xml:id="auto_poonjqc6"><p xml:id="auto_jvhh03ph">Provide pre-drawn circles with chords already outlined.</p></li>
                <li xml:id="auto_a2yxliio"><p xml:id="auto_dcs414ov">Use simpler angles (e.g., <m>60^\circ</m>, <m>90^\circ</m>) for initial practice.</p></li>
                <li xml:id="auto_zipzblj2"><p xml:id="auto_bpur5u5a">Pair struggling learners with confident problem solvers.</p></li>
                <li xml:id="auto_c7lvin2a"><p xml:id="auto_f4fpeowe">Provide step-by-step calculation templates.</p></li>
                <li xml:id="auto_ym4oy9b6"><p xml:id="auto_kmhnwfr4">Break down the formula into steps: find sector area, find triangle area, subtract.</p></li>
                <li xml:id="auto_oqmhm44m"><p xml:id="auto_t1ih760w">Allow use of calculators for trigonometric functions.</p></li>
            </ul>
        </p>
        <p xml:id="auto_tiw0hxup">
            <alert>On-Level Learners:</alert>
        </p>
        <p xml:id="auto_qlwx3qpm">
            <ul>
                <li xml:id="auto_s7zichch"><p xml:id="auto_0rzgifzj">Encourage learners to verify their formula with different angles.</p></li>
                <li xml:id="auto_asppls8u"><p xml:id="auto_pav9qgkz">Ask learners to explain the difference between a segment and a sector.</p></li>
                <li xml:id="auto_mgaqblxl"><p xml:id="auto_n3aeipfg">Provide mixed practice with different types of segment problems.</p></li>
                <li xml:id="auto_6vtnvb1w"><p xml:id="auto_e8fbnjlr">Challenge learners to find both minor and major segments.</p></li>
            </ul>
        </p>
        <p xml:id="auto_06j07xaw">
            <alert>Advanced Learners:</alert>
        </p>
        <p xml:id="auto_c4v92f9d">
            <ul>
                <li xml:id="auto_3tmthihv"><p xml:id="auto_4n5sakvm">Challenge learners to derive the formula using coordinate geometry.</p></li>
                <li xml:id="auto_6r3s7gxa"><p xml:id="auto_puorx2i7">Investigate problems where the chord length is given instead of the angle.</p></li>
                <li xml:id="auto_nrqap00q"><p xml:id="auto_0qhf2jhl">Apply the concept to find major segments using the total circle area.</p></li>
                <li xml:id="auto_tfblqyxg"><p xml:id="auto_8bgalm9q">Solve optimisation problems involving segments.</p></li>
            </ul>
        </p>
        <p xml:id="auto_fku84xt7">
            <alert>Extension Activity — Circular Park Walking Path:</alert>
        </p>
        <p xml:id="auto_cf7l9cm5">
            A circular park has a radius of <m>20</m> metres. A walking path cuts across the park, forming a chord that subtends <m>120^\circ</m> at the centre. Tasks:
            <ol marker="(a)">
                <li xml:id="auto_e8081sxo"><p xml:id="auto_jolsvpup">Draw a diagram of the circular park with the walking path.</p></li>
                <li xml:id="auto_39rqho9z"><p xml:id="auto_boz47hq8">Calculate the area of the segment formed by the walking path.</p></li>
                <li xml:id="auto_ho6wt58g"><p xml:id="auto_igab7urn">If grass costs Ksh 50 per square metre, calculate the total cost to plant grass in the segment.</p></li>
                <li xml:id="auto_68eev0bp"><p xml:id="auto_vxi2me1v">Calculate the area of the major segment (the rest of the park).</p></li>
            </ol>
        </p>
    </axiom>

